White chicken chili is the soup I most often make around here. It’s just a winner. Everyone loves it all year round.

5 TB olive oil 
1 purple onion
1 poblano pepper
2 jalapeño peppers
1 red bell pepper
5 cloves garlic, minced
Small can diced green chiles 
1 rotisserie chicken, shredded
1 12 oz bag frozen corn
1/2 C flour 
8 oz cream cheese softened 
2 cartons chicken stock 
3 TB Better than Bullion chicken base 
2 tsp salt 
1 tsp pepper
3 tsp ancho chili powder
3 tsp cumin 
2 tsp oregano 

Cook diced veggies in oil over medium heat for 15 minutes. Add minced garlic and canned chiles. Add chicken drippings (optional) and cook 5 minutes. Add 1/2 C flour and cook for 2 minutes. Add two cartons of chicken stock and turn heat to high. Whisk until it thickens a little. Add better than bullion, chicken, corn and seasonings. Stir and add softened cream cheese. Cover and simmer for 30 minutes. Whisk before serving.

Volume UP🔊 Crunchy Chicken Parm with Burrata Cheese is like a restaurant meal at home. My family puts it in the top 5 things I make! 

5-6 boneless skinless chicken breasts, trimmed / cut in half / pounded to 1/4 inch thick 

1/2 C flour + 1 tsp garlic powder + 1 1/2 tsp salt + 1 1/2 tsp pepper 

4 eggs, beaten 

I 1/2 C panko breadcrumbs + 1
1/2 C grated parmesan cheese 

Olive oil 
S&P
Burrata cheese (one ball per 2 pieces of cooked chicken)
Flakey salt 

Mix flour with garlic powder, salt and pepper in a dish. In a separate dish beat your eggs. In a third dish mix your panko and Parmesan. Yes it can be the green can kind. 

Put your chicken in the fridge guys. Don’t skip this. This is a great make ahead meal to this point. Pre-make it and then all you have to do is pan fry which is the easiest part.

Take chicken out of the fridge 30 minutes before you start cooking it. Perfect because you have to be patient and preheat your oil slowly just under medium heat. Don’t turn the heat up too high or you’ll burn the breading. This is a process that can’t be rushed. I rushed it so much when I was a new cook and always had bad batches. I almost gave up on the dish. Cook chicken 4 minutes per side if you pounded thinly enough. Trust me on these steps. Follow them and you’ll have perfect chicken parm every time.

Bang Bang Shrimp is crunchy, sweet and a little spicy. It’s definitely time consuming if you choose a small dutch oven to fry your shrimp in. I recommend a bigger pot! I also actually recommend the medium sized shrimp one size down from these (I’m cooking the large size). If you choose medium sized shrimp then fry for only 3 1/2 minutes. You need to let your oil get back up to 350 degrees after each batch is done cooking. This also means you need a thermometer. I use a candy thermometer for the job. Preheating oil takes some time so be sure to set the pot of oil over medium heat (I do it just under medium actually), first then put the lid on and start with the rest of the steps. If you’re patient and follow these steps you’ll be amazed this came from your own kitchen. Again, this is something you need to eat right away. The coating loses crunch quickly! You could even keep the sauce separate and dip each piece of shrimp in the sauce and never miss a crunch (which is one of the best parts of the dish).

1 stick kerrygold salted butter 
3 cloves garlic, minced 
2 C heavy whipping cream 
1 1/2 C grated Parmesan cheese
1/2 tsp black pepper 

Melt butter over medium heat and cook minced garlic for 2 minutes. Don’t burn the garlic. Add heavy whipping cream and whisk until full incorporated and let thicken for 10 minutes. Chopped Caprese salad is something else we will be serving on Christmas. It truly is better in my opinion than the OG for a couple reasons. When everything is the same size you do truly get perfect bites over and over. The basil pesto adds dimension without tasting out of place. It’s like it was made just for this purpose. Also fresh basil can be bitter and it will ruin a salad. The basil pesto is a fool proof way to get great taste each time. The only downfall is it’s easy to not come up for air when you’re busy scooping this salad into your mouth. 

My favorite brands to use are all sold at Kroger: Private Selection Ruby Rows and Golden Rows cherry tomatoes (they make a YUGE difference), Belgioioso mozzarella pearls, Alessi premium balsamic reduction, Private Selection Basil Pesto. I also use flakey salt to salt my tomatoes and mozzarella before adding the pesto.

The best Christmas cookies you’ll ever taste with two types of icing. I make these every year!

Cookies
3 sticks salted butter 
1 1/2 C sugar 
2 eggs
1 1/2 tsp vanilla 
3 1/2 C flour 
1 tsp baking powder 
1/2 tsp salt 

Cream together butter and sugar. Add 2 eggs and vanilla and beat until fluffy. Sift dry ingredients and slowly add to the wet. Mix til fully incorporated. Split dough into two discs, Saran Wrap them and place in fridge for an hour. Roll out between parchment paper to 1/4” thick. Cut shapes. If cookies don’t come up easily just pop dough in fridge for 30 minutes. Bake at 350 for 8 minutes and cool. 

Buttercream Frosting
2 stick kerrygold salted butter
4 C powdered sugar 
2 tsp vanilla 
2 1/2 TB milk 

Hard Icing 
4 C powdered sugar 
1 1/2 tsp vanilla
3 TB white corn syrup 
5 TB milk 

Mix powdered sugar, vanilla and corn syrup. Then add milk 1 TB at a time. Work out any lumps. 

If you want to make the swirly icing just separate some of the hard icing, add a little milk to make it slightly thinner and your desired food coloring. Drip a little on the white icing before it sets and use a toothpick to create swirls. Takes 12 hours to fully harden.

Texas Roadhouse Rolls dupe recipe. This is as close as you’re going to get to the restaurant! The cinnamon butter is literally the best thing I ever put in my mouth. I’ll be topping everything with it from now on. I actually like the homemade cinnamon butter better than the restaurant. This recipe makes 24 rolls.

Rolls
1 ¼ C 2% milk
1 egg
1 packet dry active yeast
3 TB melted butter 
¼ C honey
¼ C sugar
4 C flour 
1 tsp salt

Cinnamon Butter
1 stick salted Kerrygold butter, softened
¼ C powderd sugar
1 tsp cinnamon
2 TB honey

 

Scald your milk on medium high heat (don’t fully boil), get it just get it right to the point of a lot boil then pull off the heat and let it cool to 90 degrees. You need a thermometer for this. If your milk is too hot it will kill the yeast. Melt 3 TB butter and set aside. Once your milk is cooled to 90 degrees, add it along with honey and a yeast packet to a small bowl and allow to proof. After 15 minutes add the milk mixture to a larger bowl along with the melted butter, egg, sugar, salt and beat. Gradually add the flour. Once the dough comes together, knead for 8 minutes with a dough hook or by hand. Then knead on a floured surface 3 more minutes. Place dough in a greased bowl, cover and let rise in a warm place. I like to preheat my oven for this and then turn it off when I put the bowl in. I used to only preheat to 100 degrees but I did 200 this time and it worked great. Just be sure you TURN THE OVEN OFF before adding the bowl. Roll on a floured surface to ½ inch thick and cut in 24 squares. It’s okay if they aren’t even. Place on 2 lined baking sheets, cover with cling wrap and let rise again for 40 minutes. Bake at 350 for 12 minutes. Top with melted butter right when they come out of the oven. Mix the cinnamon butter and slather on the rolls. The cinnamon butter is what takes them over the top. Don’t be tempted to not make it. It’s a MUST.

Paella is a dish I learned to make early on in my marriage. I thought it was the prettiest one pot meal I had ever seen.  It’s an amazing way to use leftover protein. You can throw whatever protein you have in the pot,  but traditionally it’s made with seafood and smoked sausage. For this recipe we are using chicken thighs, smoked turkey sausage and shrimp. For added protein, I swapped out traditional rice for banza rice. I have been doing this lately because it’s an easy substitution and I’m always looking for more ways to add protein to my diet. If you aren’t worried about that, check out how to make your rice below.
 
13 oz pack of smoked turkey sausage (I use Eckrich) 4 boneless skinless chicken breasts, cooked and diced ½ pound large raw shelled deveined shrimp, thawed 1 purple onion, diced 1 red bell pepper, diced 6 cloves minced garlic, minced 3 TB olive oil 1/3 C white wine  1 ½ tsp salt 1 tsp pepper 1/2 tsp red pepper flakes  2 8 oz bags of banza rice, prepared and rinsed or 2 C dry rice prepared in 4 C chicken stock + ½ tsp saffron 12 oz bag frozen peas, thawed
 
Because this dish uses so much cooked protein, it’s a great option to make extra meat during the week and use that in your paella. The only thing that needs to be cooked fresh would be the shrimp because it can get tough if it’s reheated. But make my bourbon chicken earlier in the week and leave out 4 of the chicken thighs for this recipe. Then do a night of smoked sausage and mac & cheese during the week and make an extra pack of smoked sausage. I recommend the turkey sausage from Eckrich because it’s all the flavor but not overwhelmingly fatty. Just a thought. Or you can make everything fresh, it’s just more time consuming.
If you are using regular rice instead of Banza I recommend using Basmati rice. Cook it in 4 cups of chicken stock and add ½ tsp saffron to the stock if you have it. It’s an expensive spice, but it gives the rice the yellow color and flavors it.

Volume UP🔊 Crunchy Chicken Parm with Burrata Cheese is like a restaurant meal at home. My family puts it in the top 5 things I make! 

5 boneless skinless chicken breasts, trimmed / cut in half / pounded to 1/4 inch thick 

1/2 C flour + 1 tsp garlic powder + 1 1/2 tsp salt + 1 1/2 tsp pepper 

4 eggs, beaten 

I 1/2 C panko breadcrumbs + 1
1/2 C grated parmesan cheese 

Olive oil 
S&P
Burrata cheese (one ball per 2 pieces of cooked chicken)
Flakey salt 

Mix flour with garlic powder, salt and pepper in a dish. In a separate dish beat your eggs. In a third dish mix your panko and Parmesan. Yes it can be the green can kind. 

Put your chicken in the fridge guys. Don’t skip this. This is a great make ahead meal to this point. Pre-make it and then all you have to do is pan fry which is the easiest part.

Take chicken out of the fridge 30 minutes before you start cooking it. Perfect because you have to be patient and preheat your oil slowly just under medium heat. Don’t turn the heat up too high or you’ll burn the breading. This is a process that can’t be rushed. I rushed it so much when I was a new cook and always had bad batches. I almost gave up on the dish. Cook chicken 4 minutes per side if you pounded thinly enough. Trust me on these steps. Follow them and you’ll have perfect chicken parm every time.

These green beans always deserve a spot on the grid. They get wilted and become caramelized without getting stringy. If your green beans are stringy, it’s because you’re cooking them at too high of a temperature.  Slow down and do it right. Your family will thank you.

 

3-4 12 oz packages (2.25-3 lbs.) French green beans – I love Trader Joe’s haricot verts
8 TB or 1 stick Kerrygold salted butter

To a big pan (I use a cast iron skillet that takes up 2 burners) add your green beans and a little water. You don’t want to boil your green beans, rather steam. So just put a small amount of water that just covers the bottom of the pan. Turn heat to medium and cook until the green beans become bright green. You may need to move them around. Once they’re all bright green, turn the heat to low. If the water hasn’t fully cooked out then sop up the rest with paper towels. Add a stick of Kerrygold salted butter and allow to fully melt. Toss the green beans so each one is covered in butter. Move around every 10 minutes. This can take up to an hour. Salt them, toss and serve. You won’t believe how good these are.

Tortellini Soup has replaced lasagna soup. Why? Because tortellini fits on a spoon and lasagna noodles do not. Y’all really trying to eat those noodles with that spoon 😂 this is so much easier and not to mention tortellini has cheese stuffed inside 🤤 Here’s my suggestion, use sweet Italian sausage the first time you make it. It needs to be made in its original form first. Then you can do what I do and make it more macro friendly. Because I was in a hurry I didn’t brown the meat first LIKE AN IDIOT. That adds so much flavor. So START with browning the meat. We want it caramelized people. This takes a lil time. Do it just a hair under medium heat. Brown bits are our friend. Full instructions are below since this video is a hot mess.

1 lb sweet Italian sausage 
1 yellow onion, diced 
5 cloves garlic, minced 
2 TB sherry cooking wine to deglaze pan after cooking meat and onions
28 oz can crushed tomatoes 
6 oz can tomato paste 
36 oz chicken stock (one box) 
1 tsp Italian seasoning 
1 tsp salt
1/2 tsp pepper 
8 oz cream cheese, softened (one block)
36 oz frozen tortellini 
Handful fresh spinach leaves 

Brown sweet Italian sausage for 15 min.
Add the diced onion and cook 10 min. Add the minced garlic and cook 2 min more. Then add the crushed tomatoes, tomato paste, chicken stock and seasoning. Stir. Cover. Simmer for 30 min. Turn heat to high and add the cream cheese. Whisk until it’s fully incorporated. Add frozen tortellini, cook 2-3 minutes. Add spinach. Stir and serve. 

**test your tortellini after 2-3 min, yours may need more time but mine didn’t.**
